 to the oneiric beyond Freudian psychoanalysis. By reading the oneiric within variously known cultural texts – including Holocaust fiction, world cinema, Bronx theatre, surrealist art and two collections of wartime dream transcriptions – the volume also offers a renewed perspective on modern and contemporary trauma. In so doing, it demonstrates the relevance of the oneiric, beyond the interpretative framework of psychoanalysis, as an aesthetic and political tool with which to alert us and respond to the violence of our contemporary world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDreams and the arts. 0aPsychic trauma. 4aFilm and Media Studies 2022. 4aGothic 2022. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aHolocaust.  aNazism.  aSigmund Freud.  aatrocity.  adreams.  amodernity.  aoneiricism.  apsychoanalysis.  atrauma.  aunconscious.1 aBaker, Emily-Rose, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaker, Emily-Rose, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChernoff, Carolyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuffy, Helena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGucsa, Magdolna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHether, Rob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHiraide, Lydia Ayame, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKul-Want, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOki, Michiko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOtosaka, Diane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOtosaka, Diane, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSaint, Nigel, econtributor.4c